properties.name: Flinders Street
properties.description: Named for Matthew Flinders, explorer of what is now called Australia, wrote "A Voyage to Terra Australis" which was published just before his death (Mathew, 2008, p. 49). Macintyre (2004) suggests that it was Flinders who came up with the name Australia since it was, in Flinders' words, "more agreeable to the ear" (p. 50).
properties.refs:
Macintyre, S. (2004). A Concise History of Australia (2nd ed.). Port Melbourne, VIC: Cambridge University Press.

Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Melton Terrace
properties.description: Named for John Melton Black (Mathew, 2008, p. 85). In an article from the Townsville Daily Bulletin, W. J. Doherty (1934) argues that Melton, "came to a coastal creek in North Queensland and planted a city" (p. 9).
properties.refs:
Doherty, W. J. (1934, July 10). John Melton Black: The founder of Townsville. Townsville Daily Bulletin, p. 9.
Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: King Street
properties.description: Named for Phillip Parker King, explored "the coastline from Hervey Bay to Torres Strait" starting in 1817 for four and half years (Mathew, 2008, p. 72).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Wickham Street
properties.description: Named for Captain John Clements Wickham who, on board the HMS Beagle, surveyed the Australian coast (Mathew, 2008, p. 126).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Landsborough Street
properties.description: Named for William Landsborough, leader of the QLD search party for the Burke and Wills expedition. Changing course in response to Frederick Walker's search, Landsborough headed south and ended up, "the beautiful ‘downs’ country through which the Leichhardt River flows" (Mathew, 2008, p. 74).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: McKinley Street
properties.description: Named for "John McKinlay [who] was in charge of a relief party searching for Burke and Wills" (Mathew, 2008, p. 80).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Rose Street
properties.description: According to Mathew (2008), it was "either named after the flowering bush or, more likely misspelt, after C.S. Rowe an early pioneer in the settlement of Townsville" (p. 108).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Howitt Street
properties.description: Named for Alfred W. Howitt, a member of the Burke and Wills expedition who, "found the sole survivor of the party, John King, near Coopers Creek on 15th September 1861." (Mathew, 2008, p. 64)
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Roper Court
properties.description: "Named for the Roper River in the NT" (Mathew, 2008, p. 108). That river was named for John Roper (1822-1895), explorer and civil servant.
properties.refs:
Australian Dictionary of Biography. (2019). Roper, John (1822-1895). Retrieved from http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/roper-john-4503.
Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Mitchell Street
properties.description: Named for Sir Thomas Livingstone Mitchell, surveyor in the early 19th century. He is famous for "discovering" Australia Felix, a region also called Port Philip, that he described as "splendid and extensive [... that] was different from any thing I had ever witnessed either in New South Wales or elsewhere, a land so inviting, and still without inhabitants." (Mitchell cited in Haydon, 1846, p. 14)
properties.refs:
Haydon, G. H. (1846). Five years experience in Australia Felix, comprising a short account of its early settlement and its present position, with many particulars interesting to intending emigrants. London, U.K.: Hamilton, Adams, & Co. Paternoster Row.
Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.
